segments.text: feeling about finally getting into the war well it wasn't really that you know I was glad to get in the war I just felt like it was a continuation of what I'd been doing right I had been accepting all the assignments been given to me and it's been my lot to stay in the states four years my wife was with me all that time sure I'd had even though it was black outfit we'd had
pretty good success.
We'd had lots of accommodations, and so the assignment to Europe... You did have a lot of accommodations?
Oh, we did.
We did.
Uh, both as individual, uh, individuals and units, and we accomplished a lot of things.
But, uh, really, it was just another assignment.
I didn't really feel like, well, here I come in Europe, or gosh, I've got to go to Europe.
You know, just, that's it.
You just wanted to do your duty regardless of it.
That's correct.
Okay, then when you got overseas, can you tell me about your assignment there?
Yeah, we left the States sometime in February.
Went to Europe, had a
Really had a fine trip over as far as war trips go.
We were on a South American liner of the Uruguay, which was a converted pleasure.
Very nice ship.
5,000 troops.
And the officers were traveling in a different status than a lot of people did.
We ate courtesy of the ship.
So you probably had good food.
Oh, gosh.
We had a printed menu.
Printed menu.
And the table of four officers had an individual waiter.
We did.
Now that sounds strange to a lot of people for a troop ship at that stage of the war, but we did.
We had a Hungarian boy that waited on the table.
And we had a printed menu, and we ate three meals a day.
The darndest thing that you've ever seen.
It was absolutely...
I brought one of the menus home, and my wife couldn't believe it.
How about the enlisted men?
What kind of treatment did they have?
Well, they ate in child lines, and they had good food.
It was... Because I went many times down through the child lines with them, but they...
They, like all the other troop ship soldiers, I'm sure, lined up and went through a sort of a fix-your-tray-line type thing.
And I never did understand that.
It really was not good for morale, I'm sure.
No.
But that was the dictates.
We paid for this.
The U.S. government?
Oh, I'm sure they did.
In other words, they just hired a Took over the ship in some manner.
However they And it was run by Uruguayans?

I don't really know who ran the ship, but they called it No, it was a South American liner, probably headquartered in New York or somewhere prior to the war, but I really don't know who owned the Uruguay.
It was a
But it was a pleasure boat of some sort.
But this Hungarian cabin boy, he was some cabin boy.
One of the things that was always interesting to me, he felt offended if you wouldn't take a little bit of each entree on his menu.
Oh, sir, he was so good, you know.
He was just trying to promote his food.
But he was right.
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
So, how much did he gain, how many pounds did he gain on that trip?
I was doing pretty smart.
But it was a 12-day voyage.
The first three of them were, we went up high in the Atlantic and it was a rough, rough seas.
We went convoy.
I remember the ships, I mean a lot of them.
Destroyers?
Yes.
You could see them circling all the way around.

first three days we had terribly rough seas we got in one storm that it was so rough that it broke some of the lifeboats off of the davits and that you could hear them falling down the side of the ship and i was on duty one morning with my troops and uh sitting a chair at the head of the stairs and it got so rough that i just had to hold around the rail you know you couldn't you're
nothing would stay still.
Garbage cans would come down the hallways and people try to walk and you'd have to hold on to rails you know it it was terribly rough.
I never did get sick but I sure didn't feel good for a couple of days.
But finally it's moved out and we got on over to
landed in Le Havre.
We missed England.
At that time they were going directly into France.
They had opened up Le Havre and we went in on a temporary pier that they had built.
And that was in February 1945?
1945, that's correct.
And we were moved out to one of the camps out from Le Havre where they
set you up to de-process and get your equipment back with you and unwrap it.
All tools had to be wrapped and waterproofed and all this to go overseas.
We got all of our shop trucks back and got the tools unwrapped and got ready to be operational.
And we were ordered up to Hasselt, Belgium.

real interesting one of the movies recently where Eisenhower had to meet with Montgomery to straighten out some command problems they went to Hasselt and it showed the depot up there and here's Hasselt, Belgium that sort of brought back memories to me.
Did you ever did you ever get to see either one of those?
No not over there.
So we went on we went to Hasselt and uh
I was just entirely on my own.
Nobody told me where to camp or where to put up or whatever.
So I sent one of my officers out to find us a villa to live in.
The British had the town majors who were sort of like mayors who had taken over for management and running various towns.
We found an empty villa.
And so we went to the town major, and he said, move in.
So we moved in, moved the whole company in this big Belgian villa.
Was that like a hotel then?
No, just a big home.
Just a big home.
And it was about three stories, big grounds.
Had my company office there.
All the vehicles would be parked around on the grounds.
And then the officers and the key non-commissioned officers were authorized to go out and live on the economy, that is, have quarters.
We'd go find some Belgian that was willing to take us in his home, and we lived in their homes.
And I know they were reimbursed in some manner, but this town major would take us.
Like you're renting a room from them?
Yeah, that's right.
Really?
Yeah.
How'd you get along with those people?
Real fine.
They were really receptive to us, of course.
They were happy to be on board.
Another awesome... Room and board?
No, just room.
We ate with the company.
I lived with an old Belgian lady and her teenage daughter.
Her husband was a captive.
The daughter had been captured and still was unheard from.
One son had been, he had gone off to the RAF and he'd been shot down.
So they were really tied up in the war.
And they'd have one fireplace in the whole building.
We'd sit around at night, you know, running their fire and they'd talk.
They spoke English.
Enough we could understand.
Yeah.
Her husband was a mining engineer, and the Germans had captured him, and I'm sure had used his mining talents.
But we had a real interesting living there.
We stayed there about 30 days, and finally were ordered to liaise Belgium to be assigned to a depot, a big engineer depot.
It was straddle of the Albert Canal and several of those other canals there, and all the supplies came in by water.
And this depot unloaded everything with cranes.
That's a drag line crane.
They had about 40 of those things in that depot, and my job was to maintain those cranes and take equipment that had come back off the front and either repair it
or salvage it, whichever.
If it was where we could feasibly repair it and put it back in the depot, we'd do so.
Now that's water pumps, bulldozers, motor graders, any type of engineer equipment.
It would come back.
Were your men trained well enough?
That's right.
They were trained to do this work.
That's correct.
We had shops where we could make parts, you know, relays.
Machine shops, all these mobile type machine shops where they had all these things in these closed-in cab type trucks.
Very talented group of people.
And it was our sole responsibility when a piece of equipment came back to say that it's either repaired or thrown away.
My shop officer had that sole responsibility.
It was his judgment to say we fix it or throw it away.
If we fixed it, it went back into the depot.
If it was not salvable in any manner, then the depot would issue a new one to the using unit.
So we got some stuff back off the front that was in terrible shape.
I would imagine.
But it was interesting.
It was really an interesting assignment.
We stayed with that until, oh, must have been about somewhere like October or November of that year.
The war was over.
We had been in the States so long, we didn't have many points.
You know what points were.
We didn't have many, or I didn't have many points.
So I was not eligible for rotation.
Let me back up just a little bit.
We were originally scheduled to go to the South Pacific, but the war was over, so we did not go, and we stayed in that area because they didn't have many points.
What was there to do now that the damage from the battle was over?
Well, after we got

After we got sidetracked from going to Europe, I mean to South Pacific, then I was assigned to this labor supervision company because of my engineering ability, background, and that was a German staffed company.
It was German PWs.
Really?
German PWs.
That's fascinating.
German soldiers and German officers.

Okay, well let's talk about that in a minute here, but before we leave your last assignment, let's just, you were in the northern, let's talk about this, you were in the northern zone, which was basically the zone of the British Army under Montgomery.
What were the relationships, what were the relations like between the American and British soldiers, do you remember?
I had no contact to that problem.
I've
I operated under this depot commander, and I never got in combat at all.
Right, but I just thought that maybe you mightyou never repaired any British equipment?
No.
They had their own That's right.
The only thingeverybody knew of the problem, and everybody talked about the British, and all they could do was convoy up and down the road and stop for tea when it came time to do so.
You know, we didn't have...
But it was sort of common knowledge that there was a problem?
Oh, yes, absolutely.
But how profound do you think this problem was?
Or was it just a matter of the Americans or, you know, the Yangs making fun of the British?
No, I think it was a real problem.
I think it really was.
And I think the big part of it, and, of course, I've learned a lot of this subsequent, was in the upper structures of command.
Yeah, sure.
There's no question it was a problem.
I expect as far as an American soldier or American company working with a British company, there probably wasn't any of that.
It's a matter of getting along.
But it's common knowledge, but I had no contact with that sort of thing at all.
Okay, now let's move on.
Then the war is over.
Let's move on to the labor.
Okay.
the labor company.
What was your job there for such to find them?

Okay I was assigned to command this labor supervision company which was I believe about 250 German PWs and there was I believe I had three German officers at that time and we were winterizing and electrifying these redeployment camps where the soldiers were coming back
to go through Marseilles and go home or wherever.
And these camps were where they came in.
Their equipment was all turned in.
They were issued new clothes.
Records were all processed so that they could go from there directly to Marseilles to get on a boat.
That's the reason they called it a redeployment camp.
We were taking these tents, these big paramdo tents, putting wood floors in them,
putting wood parapets around the edges to protect them from the cold weather, putting electric lights into them, and building streets and roads around through them.
But I was one of about 10 of those labor supervision companies in this one camp, one headquarters.
Where was this in France?
It was in Calais, north of Marseille.
We had this prisoner of war camp with, I expect there were 6,000 PWs.
I imagine there were.
And real strange, PWs guarded the PWs.
Really?
Yeah.
That is strange.
Yeah.
We had German PWs on the gate.
Of course, we'd have an American sergeant there, but we didn't have near enough Americans to do all the guarding.
But you didn't have to worry about those guys being in camp at night, because the French would catch them out, and then they wouldn't even come back.
That's right.
So at nighttime, those Germans wanted to be in that camp, in that compound.
So they went out and worked as a company in this Calais area.
I had one engineer officer in my company, and then three Germans, and they were...
not graduate engineers, but engineers to the degree that they could supervise carpentry and electric and this sort of thing.
They supervised these 250 people during the day, marshed them back at night, and put them in the compound.
And I had to inspect the work and see that it
The officers signed the morning report.
What was the quality of the work?
Excellent.
Good workers?
Excellent.
Every one of them knew a trade.
Really?
Every German had some skill.
That's something that we could pattern after.
We had a little craft shop there where we'd let them work off times and build various things, you know.
And one of them might be a wood inlayer.

another might be a brick mason another one an expert at electricity and you know various things they could just absolutely fascinate you with the craftsmen that they were so it was a it was an interesting assignment I was with that from oh I guess this September October whenever until the next February
General Butler had quite a few good things to say about the quality of German soldiers.
Would you agree?
Oh, absolutely.
They were absolutely outstanding.
Outstanding.
How could you compare a German soldier with American soldiers?
Well, I'd say across the board he was as good or better.
When I say as good or better, they were strong.
I guess they were more specialists than our people were.
But I think it must have been a dictate from parents or somebody over there.
They had to learn a trade of some kind.
And they were highly skilled.
Did you ever get to know the German officers?
Did you ever converse with them?
Or did they only speak German?
Or did you ever have any personal relations with them?
Well, the German officers that I had could not speak English, so I really didn't discuss much with them except direct them to go over this and that.
But there were about 15 or 16 American officers in this camp, and we each had our own little
headquarters or on little quarters and we had German orderlies to take care of the cleaning and this sort of thing and I conversed with those people to a great degree.
We picked most of them because they could speak English and they'd come and clean our quarters and make our beds and wash our clothes and you know various things like that.
And I had an interesting
The one that I had was from the Russian sector of Germany.
He was happy to be in France.
He didn't want to go home.
He didn't want to go home.

And he told me, and this was real strange, and I didn't really take it at the time as being insubordinate, but he told me, he said, Captain, he said, Americans will learn that they fought the wrong people.
And at the time, it didn't make much of an impact.
But I have thought about that 10,000 times.
He was so right.
He was absolutely so right.
But here's a little private, a little insignificant private.
And he was so apologetic.
He said, pardon me, sir.
I want to tell you something.
I beg your pardon.
You know, they were real humble when they went down.
He said, Americans will learn that they fought their own people.
The private show didn't know what he was talking about.
It would really be interesting to know what happened to that little fella, because he told me he didn't know anything.
But it was a great experience I had.
Yeah, to be in command of this.
That's right.
I learned a whole lot from him.
It was something different.
How about food and health and living conditions for prisoners of war?
Let's move this over here.
How about things like that, food, health, living conditions for the prisoners of war?
Well, the only ones I know of were the ones that I was directly in contact with.
They had little tents.
And we provided some beds.
And the Red Cross had provided some blankets for them to put on.
There wasn't much to their beds.
Most of them were made probably out of boards or some plywood or something like that.
But they had adequate food.
It was prepared in one central kitchen in this compound.
Of course, I really didn't have any responsibility for preparing the food, and I never ate over there, but I know that they told me they had plenty.
It was hot, and it wasn't a bunch of goop all mixed up.
It was food that was prepared properly.
So I think my particular compound, I doubt that they had very much to complain about.
Had plenty of food.
In other words, the prisoners of war you thought were treated fairly well after a rather savage six-year ordeal.
That's right.

I imagine from the last probably two years of their service, wherever they were, with the destitute conditions that Jeremy had gotten in, I'm sure they were a whole lot better off in an American compound being looked after.
than they were back in their homeland scratching for something to eat.
Because Germany was starving in 1945, 1946.
Absolutely.
Did you have an opportunity to travel to Germany?
Yes, just to go.
On like a leave?
No, just get in the vehicle and drive up just to look.
But not to speak of.
The only thing that I really saw of Germany was I got to know an Air Force pilot, and he took me one time on a reconnaissance flight.
We went up over Aachen, Cologne, the Bavarian Alps, just made a big circle up the Ruhr and the Rhine to look at the damage and the bombs.
That's the most extensive opportunity to see Germany that I got was in an A-26, when these attacked bombers.
And other than that, I'd just get in the Jeep, and we'd just drive across the border and come back.
But I saw a whole lot of Europe, because when I had this engineering maintenance company, they assigned one of my platoons to Antwerp.
And to get there, I had to go through, go into, of course, from Belgium to Holland and then up into Antwerp.
And they were in Antwerp while the buzz bombs were falling.
In fact, my company got a bronze star or whatever it was because of the buzz bombs falling.
My troops were up there helping maintain the port equipment
at the port of Antler.
Keep the port open.
Right.
And the Germans tried to knock the port out, of course.
But that sojourn with the Germans was something that I'm glad is on the record.
Were you happy to come home in 1946?
Oh, absolutely.
And I had not been there, of course, near like a lot of them.
I was really just gone a year.
I left in February and got back in February but I was of course glad to get home.
A couple of strange things.
I really don't know how I got assigned to this transportation company coming home but I was assigned to a transportation company and I forgot whether I listed it down there or not but
No, these were the labor suit.
Anyhow, the company that I came home with was a transportation company.
And of course, all the shipping was under the transportation court.
So belonging to a transportation company, we sort of got a little favored treatment on the way home.
because we were transportation, and of course the ship was transportation.
Right, right.
So you had a pleasure craft on the way over and on the way back.
But I did get some assignments.
I was assigned as the police and prison officer for the ship coming home, which meant that I had to see that the place was cleaned up and kept orderly and all this all over the ship.
That was my assignment coming home.
But the fact that I was on the
So the staff, the captain of the ship, whatever they called him at that time, had me eat with him a number of times in his cabin.
I came back on a Liberty ship, a Victory ship, I guess it was.
But I did have an interesting assignment coming home.
I made many trips around that ship in those 12 days because I'd have to go

in the morning first thing and then when the colonel inspected the ship i had to go back and travel over the whole ship with him when he made his inspection and he went every day too so the time must have gone pretty fast it did it was i enjoyed having some responsibility but uh eating with the captain was almost like eating with the uh with the uh south american liner i betcha and
Another strange coincidence, we left out, I guess it's strange, we left out, we went through Weehawken, New Jersey, went to New York, Pier 31, I believe it was, boarded the ship.
Coming back, we got off on Pier 31, got on a ferry boat, went right back to Weehawken,
right back to Camp Cameron, New Jersey.
I mean, exactly backtrack.
Didn't even, same pier, got off the same pier.
So that's, that is sort of strange.
I was, I was wondering, you were discharged from active duty in 1946.
Many people in America were rather worried about falling back into a depression after the war.
about job opportunities or a number of popular opinion polls taken, which all demonstrated that the American people were slightly or rather insecure about their future.
Were you at all worried about your future when you got out in 1946?
No, because I had a leave of absence from the highway department, had a guaranteed return job, and the highway department had
had not been able to expend monies on highways for four years because of material and equipment.
And they were 20 years behind.
They had tons of work.
Had tons of work and lots of money to do it with.
And it was a matter of them getting geared up to do it.
And they were taking back everybody that left them
and a lot of people that wanted to come back and work.
So really, I had a very bright future.
No problems at all.
I went right back to work.
And we just had work running out our ears.
So I was not faced with that problem.
Would you consider that you had indefinite aims and goals when you got out of the service in 46?
Oh, yeah.
I was going back to the highway department to be a highway engineer.
That was my aim from the time I was 11 years old.
Right.
I was still in the same pipeline.
Okay.
Now, then let's turn back to your career again, your post-war career in the Reserves.
Why'd you decide to stay in the Reserves?
Well, I had heard some of the people back in the late 20s and early 30s talk about the interest they'd had in the Reserve and
The fact that it had enhanced them during World War II.
A lot of them had been promoted over those years.
A lot of them had gotten a lot of longevity.
And so I went to looking for a place that I could get in an active reserve outfit.
Also, it was thought that there would be a retirement someday for a reserve program.
I'm not I don't know exactly what the status of retirement was at that time but I think there was a program whereby at the end of 20 years you you had some built-in uh yeah uh
